article.headline: Suns 0-3 under interim coach
article.linkText: Kings rally from 15 down to snuff Suns
article.story:
SACRAMENTO, Calif. (AP) -- Mike D'Antoni watched the Phoenix Suns let his first NBA coaching victory slip away. Peja Stojakovic tied a season high with 36 points, helping rally the Sacramento Kings to a 107-102 victory over the struggling Suns on Sunday night. Phoenix missed 22 of 26 shots in the fourth quarter, squandering a 13-point lead. "We knew that if we weren't going to score, they would come back," D'Antoni said. "This team (the Kings) is a high-powered team. And they were going to put up a lot of points." Sacramento outscored Phoenix 28-10 in the fourth quarter, sending the Suns to their sixth straight loss and dropping D'Antoni to 0-3 since taking over for fired Frank Johnson. Stojakovic scored 25 points in the second half, 16 in the third period. He hit five 3-pointers, made 11 of 22 shots and all nine free throws. Stojakovic's biggest basket was a short baseline jumper with 4:16 remaining, putting the Kings ahead for good at 100-98. "I think we got lucky, we can't afford to keep doing that," Stojakovic said. "When you're trying to do that you never know what's going to happen, especially down 10 or more." Brad Miller added 17 points, Doug Christie had 14, and Bobby Jackson had 13 points and nine rebounds for the Kings, who have won four straight and are 13-1 at home. Anthony Peeler scored eight points and made a crucial tip-in of a missed shot by Miller, putting the Kings ahead 104-100 with 24.9 seconds remaining. "The fourth quarter is the time to turn it on and we were able to do that," Peeler said. Shawn Marion had 28 points and 12 rebounds for Phoenix. Stephon Marbury added 22 points and eight assists, but missed nine straight shots in the fourth quarter. Joe Johnson had 19 points and Scott Williams added 10. "We played 40 minutes tonight," Marbury said. "We're getting better, but it's not exactly where we want to be." The Kings opened the fourth quarter with a 19-4 run, going ahead 98-96 on Doug Christie's layup in traffic with 6:35 remaining. It was their first lead since late in the first period. Following a strong first half, the Suns played an even better third quarter. They managed to increase their lead to 92-79. Johnson continually hit from the perimeter as the Suns outscored Sacramento 32-27. "We had 14 turnovers in the first half that led to 20 points," Kings coach Rick Adelman said. "You can't allow them to get easy baskets. Finally we stopped letting them get easy baskets, we started challenging shots and the game changed." The Suns did not resemble a team coming off a lopsided loss the previous night against the Clippers. They shot 58 percent in the opening half, and led 60-52. Thanks in part to the Kings' suspect defense, Marion made a variety of perimeter shots and also got free inside, scoring 21 first-half points. Marbury added 16 points and seven assists.

Game notes
Sacramento made 10 of 11 shots to start the game. ... The Kings had four turnovers in their previous game at Utah and committed 14 in the first half against the Suns. ... The Suns tied an Arco Arena record for an opponent with 13 steals in the opening half.
